## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown by the runtime |

`Thread.Abort` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire mid-`finally` block, leave locks held, and corrupt shared data.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must observe the CancellationToken for reliable cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates to match original behavior.
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async-native overload — preferred when callers are already async.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework) — work is blind to cancellation
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowComputation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work observes the token
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowComputation(ct),   // pass token inward
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.** If `work` never checks the token, it runs to completion even after timeout. Thread.Abort was "rude" — cancellation tokens are polite. For CPU-bound loops:

```csharp
// Inside your work delegate — check periodically
for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
{
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    // ... compute ...
}
```

**2. Uncooperative third-party code.** If you truly cannot modify the work (e.g., a library call with no cancellation support), isolate it in a separate **process**, not a thread. A fire-and-forget task leak is the lesser evil:

```csharp
// Last resort — the task may keep running after timeout
public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
        return task.Result;

    // Task still runs on a thread pool thread — cannot kill it.
    // Log it, but don't wait.
    _ = task.ContinueWith(t => t.Exception, TaskContinuationOptions.OnlyOnFaulted);
    throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
}
```

**3. `Task.Result` vs `await`.** The sync overload uses `task.Wait()` which blocks a thread — identical to the original `Thread.Join` behavior. Prefer the `async` overload in new code to avoid threadpool starvation.
